# Walkthrough — Retailer Sales Representative Backend

## Summary

Built a complete NestJS backend for managing Sales Representatives and their assigned retailers. The project includes **59 files** across 12 modules.

## Architecture

```mermaid
graph TD
  Client -->|JWT| Auth["Auth Module"]
  Client -->|GET/PATCH| Retailers["Retailers Module"]
  Client -->|POST/DELETE| Admin["Admin Module"]
  Client -->|CRUD| CRUD["Region/Area/Distributor/Territory"]
  
  Retailers -->|Cache| Redis["Redis"]
  Retailers --> Prisma["Prisma ORM"]
  Admin --> Prisma
  CRUD --> Prisma
  Auth --> Prisma
  Prisma --> PostgreSQL["PostgreSQL"]
```

## What Was Built

| Component | Files | Key Details |
|-----------|-------|-------------|
| **Auth** | 8 files | JWT login, Passport strategy, role guards, `@CurrentUser` decorator |
| **Retailers** | 5 files | Paginated listing (SR-scoped), detail (Redis-cached, 5 min TTL), update (points/routes/notes only) |
| **Admin Bulk** | 5 files | CSV import (stream-parsed, batch 500), bulk assign/unassign with `skipDuplicates` |
| **Regions CRUD** | 5 files | Full CRUD under `/admin/regions` |
| **Areas CRUD** | 5 files | Full CRUD under `/admin/areas` |
| **Distributors CRUD** | 5 files | Full CRUD under `/admin/distributors` |
| **Territories CRUD** | 5 files | Full CRUD under `/admin/territories` |
| **Infrastructure** | 4 files | PrismaModule (global), RedisModule (global, ioredis) |
| **Schema** | 2 files | Prisma schema + SQL migration with 12 indexes |
| **Seed** | 1 file | 10 regions, 50 areas, 20 distributors, 100 territories, 1000 retailers, 6 users, ~350 assignments |
| **Docker** | 3 files | Multi-stage Dockerfile, docker-compose (app + Postgres 16 + Redis 7), .dockerignore |
| **Tests** | 3 files | 15+ unit tests across auth, retailers, and admin services |
| **Docs** | 1 file | Swagger at `/api/docs`, README with full API table |

## Key Design Decisions

1. **Unified `users` table** with a `role` enum (`ADMIN`/`SR`) instead of separate `sales_reps` and `admins` tables — simpler auth, single JWT payload
2. **`sales_rep_retailers` mapping table** with composite unique index for O(1) assignment checks
3. **Redis caching** on retailer detail (most-hit endpoint) with automatic invalidation on update
4. **Batch CSV import** — stream-parsed with `csv-parse`, inserted in batches of 500 with `skipDuplicates` to handle re-imports gracefully
5. **12 database indexes** covering all foreign keys, search columns (name, phone), and the retailer UID unique index

